<br>
Does the financial success of Haliburton affect Dick Cheney?<br>
<br>
Does Dick Cheney push government policys that favor Haliburton?<br>
<br>
Both questions have a lot of evidence supporting &quot;Yes&quot; answers.  I am not aware of any evidence that supports a &quot;No&quot; answer for either question. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2105<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/26/03 2:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=205.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: heh</span><hr size=1> Actually, Cheney has no financial interest in Haliburton at this point.  He took out an insurance policy before entering the White House so that he receives exactly the same payments whether or not Haliburton goes out of business and regardless of what the stock does.  This was done so he didn't have any financial interest in the company.<br>
<br>
You can argue he's helping out his friends, and you might be able to support that, but it's financially irrelevant to him now what happens to Haliburton.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=anywon>Anywon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I can't decide on a title</span><br>  Posts: 852<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/26/03 3:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=205.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Cheney</span><hr size=1> If Cheney has no financial interest in Haliburton, then how do you explain the stock options and the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>deferred salary</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (meaning he will be paid the salary once he is no longer Vice President). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2107<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/26/03 3:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=205.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cheney</span><hr size=1> See above, I thought it was clear in the above post.  I'll try to be more explicit.<br>
<br>
Say he's due to get $100,000 of deferred salary per year for 10 years.  (Obviously fake numbers, to illustrate a point.)<br>
<br>
He agrees to pay all of the money he receives from Haliburton to, say, Prudential (I have no clue which insurance company it is).  In exchange, Prudential agrees to pay him $95,000 (or some amount) per year, regardless of what happens to Haliburton.<br>
<br>
Thus, we consider 2 scenarios.<br>
<br>
1) Haliburton stays in business, Haliburton pays $100k/yr for 10 years to Prudential.  Prudential pays Dick Cheney $95k/yr for 10 years.  Dick Cheney makes $950,000 over 10 years.<br>
<br>
2) Haliburton folds entirely and goes out of business.  Haliburton pays nothing to Prudential.  Prudential pays Dick Cheney $95k/yr for 10 years.  Dick Cheney makes $950,000 over 10 years.<br>
<br>
Either way, he makes the same amount.<br>
<br>
The options are dealt with similarly.  Essentially what happens is that they are bought out at theoretical value (determined by either Black Scholes or binomial/trinomial modelling) and Dick Cheney gets a fixed amount regardless of what the stock does.<br>
<br>
It really doesn't matter to him what happens to Haliburton.  He released all the details of this insurance policy to make it absolutely clear that he would not profit in any way from contracts given to Haliburton.<br>
<br>
